        &lt;/TextBlock.TextDecorations&gt;
    &lt;/TextBlock&gt;
    &lt;TextBlock Text=&quot;2019-10-07 17:00&quot; /&gt;

I don&#39;t have an answer to why this odd behavior occurs. It looks like the dashes created by the `Pen` are mapped to the decorated text of the `TextDecoration`. This makes sense as the dashes or `TextDecoration` in general will automatically adjust to the e.g. font size. The minus character seems to produce a different spacing. Maybe this behavior doesn&#39;t occur when using a monospace font.

Anyway, you could create a tiled `DrawingBrush` and assign it to the `Pen.Brush` property to create the dashed line. You can play around with the [`DrawingBrush.ViewPort`][1] to alter the position or the length of the dashes.  
The `Viewport` consists of four values and is actually a `Rect` that describes the tile&#39;s position and dimension: `x, y, width, height`. Bigger values for width and height create longer dashes.  
The result is an even drawing of dashes and spaces:

    &lt;TextBlock Text=&quot;2019-10-07 17:00&quot;&gt;
      &lt;TextBlock.TextDecorations&gt;
        &lt;TextDecoration Location=&quot;Underline&quot;&gt;
          &lt;TextDecoration.Pen&gt;
            &lt;Pen&gt;
              &lt;Pen.Brush&gt;
                &lt;DrawingBrush Viewport=&quot;0,0,10,10&quot;
                              ViewportUnits=&quot;Absolute&quot;
                              TileMode=&quot;Tile&quot;&gt;
                  &lt;DrawingBrush.Drawing&gt;
                    &lt;GeometryDrawing Brush=&quot;Black&quot;&gt;
                      &lt;GeometryDrawing.Geometry&gt;
                        &lt;GeometryGroup&gt;
                          &lt;RectangleGeometry Rect=&quot;0,0,5,5&quot; /&gt;
                          &lt;RectangleGeometry Rect=&quot;5,5,5,5&quot; /&gt;
                        &lt;/GeometryGroup&gt;
                      &lt;/GeometryDrawing.Geometry&gt;
                    &lt;/GeometryDrawing&gt;
                  &lt;/DrawingBrush.Drawing&gt;
                &lt;/DrawingBrush&gt;
              &lt;/Pen.Brush&gt;
            &lt;/Pen&gt;
          &lt;/TextDecoration.Pen&gt;
        &lt;/TextDecoration&gt;
      &lt;/TextBlock.TextDecorations&gt;
    &lt;/TextBlock&gt;

The downside of this approach is that the size and position of the dashes is no longer adaptive to the size of the font.

  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.windows.media.tilebrush.viewport?view=netframework-4.8#remarks

This is probably a result of some weird dash-hack found in the WPF glyph rendering code. In the .NET source you will find the [AdjustAdvanceForDisplayLayout()](https://referencesource.microsoft.com/#PresentationCore/Core/CSharp/System/Windows/Media/GlyphRun.cs,77abc8044cc1ca2f,references) method and its comment:

    // AdvanceHeight is used to compute the bounding box. In some case, eg. the dash
    // character &#39;-&#39;, the bounding box is computed to be empty in Display
    // TextFormattingMode (because the metrics are rounded to be pixel aligned) and so the
    // dash is not rendered!

Setting `TextOptions.TextFormattingMode=&quot;Display&quot;` on the `TextBlock` will produce a slightly different artifact:

[![enter image description here][1]][1]

This tells us that we did indeed hit this &quot;workaround&quot; (see `GlyphRun.cs` line [1326](https://referencesource.microsoft.com/#PresentationCore/Core/CSharp/System/Windows/Media/GlyphRun.cs,1326)).

So the question is if we can somehow get a third variant, without any of these artifacts. So far, I have not succeeded but I did try to find where this hyphen check occurs. It seems to happen in native code. See [TextFormatterContext.cs](https://referencesource.microsoft.com/#PresentationCore/Core/CSharp/System/Windows/Media/TextFormatting/TextFormatterContext.cs,506) and [LoCreateContext](https://referencesource.microsoft.com/#PresentationCore/Core/CSharp/MS/Internal/TextFormatting/LineServices.cs,1701).



  [1]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/NKQZ5.png
  [2]: https://referencesource.microsoft.com/#PresentationCore/Core/CSharp/System/Windows/Media/TextFormatting/TextFormatterContext.cs,112

